course_metadata.title: Energy citizenship, inequalities and socio technical transitions

content_chunks.content: This course delves into the multifaceted relationship between energy systems and society. It begins by tracing the historical context and evolution of energy citizenship, setting the stage for a critical examination of socio-technical transitions and the transformative role of technology in societal change. Participants will explore the complexities of energy systems and their interactions with social structures, focusing on the pressing issue of social inequalities in energy access. Through an analysis of energy poverty and its impacts, students will gain insight into the ethical implications of energy policies and the concept of energy justice. The course emphasizes the importance of citizen engagement, highlighting effective methods and showcasing successful case studies of participation in energy decision-making. Participants will investigate energy communities within the framework of EU directives and learn about policy frameworks that support energy citizenship.

Technology for energy citizenship development and socio-technical transitions implementation - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in energy citizenship concepts and socio-technical transitions frameworks using advanced energy system analysis and energy inequality assessment methodologies. Students will master energy poverty analysis techniques, energy justice principles application, and energy policy ethics evaluation for optimal citizen engagement strategies and energy community development. The curriculum focuses on practical EU energy directives compliance, digital citizen participation tools utilization, and decentralized energy systems design for comprehensive smart grid technologies integration and energy cooperative formation. Participants will gain hands-on experience with behavioral change theories application, energy behavioral economics implementation, and renewable energy adoption strategies for energy democracy promotion. The program emphasizes interdisciplinary approaches to energy system transformation, social structure integration, and technology-driven societal change for creating equitable and just energy futures.

content_chunks.title: Introduction to Energy Citizenship. Historical context and evolution
Understanding Socio-Technical Transitions. Concepts and frameworks of socio-technical transitions. Role of technology in societal change
Energy Systems and Society. Overview of energy systems. Interaction between energy systems and society
Social Inequalities in Energy Access. Types of energy inequalities (economic, geographic, social). Impacts of energy poverty
Energy Justice and Ethical Considerations. Ethical implications of energy policies
Citizen Engagement in Energy Systems. Methods of citizen engagement. Case studies of successful engagement
Energy communities (EU directives and case studies)
Decentralized Energy Systems. Role of citizens in renewable energy adoption. Smart Grids
Energy Cooperatives. Formation and operation of energy cooperatives
Behavioural Change and Energy Use. Theories of behavioral change and Behavioral Economics
